<p>In the latest development in Venezuela’s political upheaval, the country’s interim authorities have begun releasing jailed Americans, and the U.S. State Department called it “an important step in the right direction”. U.S. officials did not publicly identify the people freed or specify how many were released, though multiple outlets reported that more than one American detainee was freed. The releases come after the U.S. military captured Nicolás Maduro and transported him to the United States to face federal charges, a shift that has intensified scrutiny of detentions and conditions inside Venezuelan prisons.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/52M2KzgDnggD_lgktO0p2kDPvuQmKVxDBKLWaM9R1b4jzOflvJhYp-Lrf-jPgFj41JZ01tnnMJrE8zu26LCM5wbGnmLvkJwdYAAkqf-5JEFPXO93UL4lC4ShQjBdFGJ_eHkwfCDyYuFiWJlpwfJRe00FMeY1I0SPr79EcKImjbgmBh2VvogdcybxDlBmAHAPl1V3s4zYRZ7X' alt='Family members of political prisoners holding a vigil outside of the Rodeo I detention center last week in Guatire, Venezuela.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Numbers disputed: Venezuela’s top lawmaker said more than 400 prisoners were released, while local rights groups said the total was far lower—around 70—highlighting uncertainty over who has actually been freed.</li><li>Families waiting: Hundreds of families have gathered and held vigils outside detention centers, saying authorities have not provided clear lists or timelines for releases despite public announcements.</li><li>Rights pressure: Human rights groups, international bodies and opposition figures have long demanded the release of political prisoners, and the new announcements have renewed those calls.</li><li>Maduro case: Maduro and his wife, Cilia Flores, pleaded not guilty in a U.S. court after their capture, according to reporting on the unfolding U.S.–Venezuela standoff.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>U.S. State Department: The U.S. welcomed the interim authorities’ decision to free American detainees, describing it as a constructive move while withholding names and exact numbers. (<a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cqj2qg70px9o'>BBC News</a>)</li><li>Venezuela’s interim leadership: Interim officials have presented prisoner releases as part of a broader shift after Maduro’s ouster, without consistently publishing detailed rosters of who is being freed. (<a href='https://www.france24.com/en/americas/20260114-venezuela-americans-prison-us'>France 24</a>)</li><li>Venezuelan rights groups and families: Local NGOs and relatives of detainees say official claims do not match what they are seeing on the ground, and they want transparent lists and a clear schedule for releases. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/14/world/americas/venezuela-politicial-prisoners-release.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li><li>Venezuela’s legislature leadership: A top lawmaker has publicly asserted that the number of people freed is in the hundreds, a figure disputed by rights monitors. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/1/14/venezuelas-top-lawmaker-says-more-than-400-prisoners-have-been-released'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cqj2qg70px9o'>Venezuela has freed some American citizens from prison, US official says</a> - bbc.com</li><li><a href='https://www.allsides.com/news/2026-01-14-0800/americas-venezuela-releases-multiple-american-citizens-prison-following-military-operation'>Venezuela releases multiple American citizens from prison following military operation</a> - allsides.com</li><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/venezuelas-top-lawmaker-says-over-400-prisoners-freed-ngos-say-numbers-much-lower'>Venezuela’s top lawmaker says over 400 prisoners freed, NGOs say numbers much lower</a> - straitstimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/us-lauds-freeing-of-american-prisoners-in-venezuela/a-75497232'>US lauds freeing of American prisoners in Venezuela</a> - dw.com</li><li><a href='https://www.firstpost.com/world/us-